* Create a new env:
  conda create --name <my_env_name> python=<x.x> {installs the x.x python version. Must} anaconda {add all anaconda packages. Optional}

 
* Activate an env:
  conda activate <my_env_name>
  or 
  source activate <my_env_name>
(now you can pip-install any packages in your specific env)


* Duplicate an existing env:
1. Create the requirements file:
  When the original env is activated, do:
  conda list -e > requirements.txt
2. Then create the identical env by:
  conda create --name <env> --file <this file>


* See which envs exist:
conda info --envs


* Remove (delete) env:
  conda env remove --name <env name>
